Source: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slashdot#History" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Wikipedia</a><br />
In September 2012, it was announced that Slashdot had been acquired by Dice Holdings, alongside other Geeknet websites including SourceForge and Freecode, for $20 million in cash.[2][35] Dice, owner of job listing and career websites, stated that there were no plans for major changes to Slashdot.[35] However, beginning October 1, 2013, the site is currently in &quot;beta&quot; for a new, controversial redesign that looks more like typical blog websites with the once elaborate comment system, now replaced with a simpler one at the end.[36] Many longtime users were upset with the mandatory migration to the new Beta version which provides visual enhancements yet removes many of the features that distinguished Slashdot from other news sites. An organized 'Slashcott' of the site was set for the week of February 10-17, 2014.[37] 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
<br />
I'm a long-time visitor/lurker at slashdot. I read the stories, I read the comments, and I enjoy the news digestion. For more in-depth articles, I switch over to Torrentfreak or Ars Technica, but slashdot has a higher frequency of article linkage and comments.<br />
<br />
Due to the change, and the forced-switch to the Beta, I've been looking for alternatives. altslashdot mutated into soylentnews, and will probably change one more time once they go live. However, despite my eagerness to help the new site succeed, I am open to other, similar webpages.<br />
<br />
Any recommendations?<br />
Thoughts on the way DICE is treating their userbase?</div>

